{"title_page": "Amazon Appstore", "text_new": "{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Amazon Appstore for Android\n| logo                   = Amazon.com-Logo.svg\n| logo size              = 200px\n| screenshot             = Amazon App Store.png\n| screenshot size        = 200px\n| caption                = Amazon Appstore for Android\n| developer              = [[Amazon.com]]\n| released               =  March 22, 2011\n| status                 = Active / 800,000+ apps\n| latest_release_version = release-32.52.1.0.204529.0_800923810\n| latest_release_date    = {{Start date and age|2020|3|10|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/getappstore \n|title=Install Amazon Appstore|publisher=Amazon|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n| operating_system       = [[Android Operating System|Android]]<br/>[[Fire OS]]\n| genre                  = [[Software update]], [[digital distribution]]\n| license                = [[proprietary software|Proprietary]]\n| website                = {{URL|https://www.amazon.com/getappstore}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Amazon Appstore for Android''' is an [[app store]] for the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] operating system operated by [[Amazon.com]]. It was opened on March 22, 2011 and was made available in nearly 200 countries.<ref>{{cite web|author=Amazon.com |url=https://developer.amazon.com/post/Tx3IJP9TKDQOXS5/Developers-Can-Now-Distribute-Apps-in-Nearly-200-Countries-Worldwide-on-Amazon.html |title=Developers Can Now Distribute Apps in Nearly 200 Countries Worldwide on Amazon - Amazon Mobile App Distribution Blog |publisher=Developer.amazon.com |date=2013-05-23 |accessdate=2013-11-27}}</ref> Developers are paid 70% of the [[list price]] of the app or in-app purchase.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sigitarinto.com/2011/03/22/amazon-app-store/ |title=Amazon Appstore &#124; Android |publisher=SigitArinto.com |date=2011-03-22 |accessdate=2011-04-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827070545/http://sigitarinto.com/2011/03/22/amazon-app-store/ |archivedate=2011-08-27 }}</ref>\n\nOn September 28, 2011, Amazon launched the [[Kindle Fire]] tablet.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ned Potter via Good Morning America |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/amazon-kindle-fire-announced-jeff-bezos-beat-apple/story?id=14623497 |title=Amazon Tablet: Kindle Fire Announced by Jeff Bezos to Beat Apple iPad for $199, Relative Bargain - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2011-09-28 |accessdate=2013-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2011/09/28/technology/amazon_tablet/index.htm|title=Amazon unveils $199 Kindle Fire tablet and $79 e-ink Kindle|last=Pepitone|first=Julianne|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> The tablet, designed for [[media consumption]] in the Amazon ecosystem, relies solely on the Amazon Appstore for its marketplace, eschewing [[Google Play]]. Alongside the tablet was a new design for the Amazon Appstore, intended to better integrate with the tablet's user interface.\n\nOn June 18, 2014, [[BlackBerry Limited|BlackBerry]] announced an official relationship with Amazon, which includes access to the Amazon Appstore in [[BlackBerry 10]].3.<ref name=verge-amazonapp>{{cite web|title=BlackBerry will bring thousands of apps from Amazon's store to its phones|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/6/18/5820472/blackberry-phones-getting-amazon-appstore-apps-in-bb10-3|website=The Verge|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\n\nThe Amazon Appstore included the \"Free App of the Day\" feature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andromint.com/google-play-store-vs-amazon-appstore/ |title=Amazon Appstore Compared with Google Play |work=Andromint.com |date=28 October 2013 |accessdate=2013-10-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031052750/http://www.andromint.com/google-play-store-vs-amazon-appstore/ |archivedate=31 October 2013 }}</ref>  Every day, an application, frequently a game, was offered for free. On the launch day, this game was [[Angry Birds Rio]] (Ad-Free), in itself a promotional game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2011-03-22/advertise/bal-new-amazon-android-app-store-1-free-app--day-20110322_1_app-store-free-app-amazon |title=New Amazon Android App Store - 1 Free App / Day - Baltimore Sun |publisher=Articles.baltimoresun.com |date=2011-03-22 |accessdate=2011-04-05 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110412175431/http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2011-03-22/advertise/bal-new-amazon-android-app-store-1-free-app--day-20110322_1_app-store-free-app-amazon |archivedate=12 April 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On The European launch day, the free app was [[Angry Birds (video game)|Angry Birds]] (Ad-Free). The Free App of the Day feature made an exception to Amazon's payments, instead giving the developer none of the list price during the featured day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gigaom.com/2011/07/05/amazon-appstore-not-so-amazing/ |title=Amazon Appstore, Not so Amazing |publisher=GigaOM|date=2011-07-05|accessdate=2011-07-06| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110709060730/http://gigaom.com/2011/07/05/amazon-appstore-not-so-amazing/| archivedate= 9 July 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe store's \"Test Drive\" feature allowed users to try an application in their web browser by launching a virtual copy of Android in the [[Amazon EC2]] [[cloud computing|cloud]] for half an hour.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jason Kincaid |url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/03/22/amazon-android-app-store-3/ |title=Amazon's Android App Store Launches: Test Drive Apps Directly From Your Browser |publisher=Techcrunch.com |date=2011-03-22 |accessdate=2011-04-05| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110328065244/http://techcrunch.com/2011/03/22/amazon-android-app-store-3/| archivedate= 28 March 2011| url-status= live}}</ref> The Test Drive service was decommissioned in 2015, Amazon saying that the service had been in decline, partly due to many apps not supporting the feature, and the increasing prevalence of the \"free-to-play\" business model making it obsolete.<ref>Perez, Sarah. \"Amazon Shuts Down TestDrive.\" TechCrunch. TechCrunch, 17 Apr. 2015. Web. 20 July 2015. [https://techcrunch.com/2015/04/17/amazon-shuts-down-testdrive-the-appstore-feature-that-let-you-try-apps-before-downloading/ Amazon Shuts Down TestDrive]</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Amazon introduced [[Amazon Coin]]s as a form of payment for purchasing apps, games, and [[in-app purchases]] from the store.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/may/14/amazon-coins-virtual-currency|title=Amazon launches Coins virtual currency|last=Flood|first=Alison|date=2013-05-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Android applications==\nAs of October 9, 2019, the Amazon Appstore features 487,083 applications available for download.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/307330/number-of-available-apps-in-the-amazon-appstore/|title=Amazon Appstore: number of available apps by quarter 2018 {{!}} Statistic|website=Statista|language=en|access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref>\n\nOnly a few of the most popular apps available on the Google Play Store and the [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] are also available on the Amazon Appstore. For example, [[Facebook, Inc.|the Facebook company]] offers [[Facebook]], Facebook Lite, [[Instagram]], [[Facebook Messenger|Messenger]] and [[Messenger Kids]] in all stores. However, the company does not offer [[IGTV]] separately from Instagram on the Amazon Appstore, nor does it offer [[WhatsApp]], Messenger Lite, Boomerang or Layout.\n\n===History of app growth===\nWhen the Amazon Appstore for Android launched in March 2011, it had about 3,800 apps. It reached 80,000 apps in June 2013 and 240,000 apps in June 2014.<ref>[http://www.androidcentral.com/amazon-appstore-triples-selection-240000-apps Amazon Appstore triples selection to 240,000 apps] June 2014.</ref> In June 2015, the app store had nearly 334,000 apps.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/mobile-apps/b?node=2350149011 Amazon App Store for Android]. Retrieved 23 June 2015.</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nShortly after the Amazon Appstore launch, the [[International Game Developers Association]] (IGDA) published an open letter expressing concerns that were primarily aimed at Amazon's distribution terms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://igdaboard.wordpress.com/2011/04/14/important-advisory-about-amazon%E2%80%99s-appstore-distribution-terms-2/ |title=Important Advisory about Amazon's Appstore Distribution Terms |publisher=[[International Game Developers Association]] |accessdate=2011-05-14|quote=''We are not aware of any other retailer having a formal policy of paying a supplier just 20% of the supplier's minimum list price without the supplier's permission.(...)If you ever conduct even a temporary price promotion in another market, you must permanently lower your list price in Amazon's market''| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110430031238/http://igdaboard.wordpress.com/2011/04/14/important-advisory-about-amazon%E2%80%99s-appstore-distribution-terms-2/| archivedate= 30 April 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/appsblog/2011/apr/14/amazon-android-appstore-igda |title=IGDA warns Android game developers about Amazon's Appstore terms|publisher=[[guardian.co.uk]] |date=2011-04-14 |accessdate=2011-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/34108/IGDA_Outlines_Significant_Concerns_Over_Amazon_Appstore_Terms.php |title=IGDA Outlines 'Significant Concerns' Over Amazon Appstore Terms|publisher=[[Gamasutra]] |date=2011-04-14 |accessdate=2011-05-14| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110510075823/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/34108/IGDA_Outlines_Significant_Concerns_Over_Amazon_Appstore_Terms.php| archivedate= 10 May 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> The main concerns about the conditions were that Appstore terms force developers to permanently lower their AppStore prices if ever they do promotions on other stores, and that Amazon could choose to lower the price of an application while deciding to reduce the developer's share without having to ask permission. Following this address, Amazon clarified the Appstore developer agreement,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amazonappstoredev.com/2011/04/clarification-about-amazon-appstore-developer-agreement.html |title=Clarification about Amazon Appstore Developer Agreement|publisher=[[Amazon.com, Inc.]] |date=2011-04-15 |accessdate=2011-05-14| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110511085347/http://www.amazonappstoredev.com/2011/04/clarification-about-amazon-appstore-developer-agreement.html| archivedate= 11 May 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> but this did not assuage the IGDA's concerns, which declared that \"Amazon's terms represent a threat to game developers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://igdaboard.wordpress.com/2011/04/19/amazon%E2%80%99s-clarification-fails-to-address-game-developer-concerns/ |title=Amazon's clarification fails to address game developer concerns |publisher=[[International Game Developers Association]] |date=2011-04-19 |accessdate=2011-05-14 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511093033/http://igdaboard.wordpress.com/2011/04/19/amazon%E2%80%99s-clarification-fails-to-address-game-developer-concerns/ |archivedate=11 May 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canardpc.com/news-52508-tir_de_barrage_contre_amazon.html |title=Tir de barrage contre Amazon |publisher=[[Canard PC]] |date=2011-04-14 |accessdate=2011-05-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518041449/http://www.canardpc.com/news-52508-tir_de_barrage_contre_amazon.html |archive-date=2011-05-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, the Swedish developer Bithack pulled its ''Apparatus'' application from the Appstore and published an open letter explaining that the store was a \"disaster\" for indie developers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bithack.se/news/apparatus-amazon-july-4-2011.html|title=Apparatus will be pulled from Amazon Appstore|quote=''If you are a small indie development team, or possibly even alone, don't bother with Amazon Appstore. Create a great app, publish it on Android Market, and provide great customer support. You will never succeed on Amazon Appstore without a big wallet, or at least an established reputation so that Amazon puts value behind their promises.''|publisher=bithack.se|date=2011-07-04|accessdate=2011-07-15|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110705190345/http://bithack.se/news/apparatus-amazon-july-4-2011.html|archivedate=2011-07-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> The main problems related to the very slow review process, the absence of any means to filter unsupported devices, and that Amazon changed the price of the application without consulting the developer,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/2084090/game-developer-pulls-app-amazon-appstore |title=Game developer pulls app from Amazon Appstore over problems |quote=''The final problem was that Amazon changed the price without consulting the developer. The price was cut to $0.99, only a quarter of its original price, which, while perhaps good for players, is not good for the developer.''|publisher=[[The Inquirer]] |date=2011-07-05|accessdate=2011-07-15}}</ref> leading to the IGDA reiterating its warnings concerning Amazon's policy once again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2011/07/08/igda-still-unhappy-with-amazon-appstore-policies/|title=IGDA still unhappy with Amazon Appstore policies|publisher=Joystiq|date=2011-07-08|accessdate=2011-07-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714112306/http://www.joystiq.com/2011/07/08/igda-still-unhappy-with-amazon-appstore-policies/|archive-date=2011-07-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Accusation of trademark infringement by Apple ==\n{{See also|Apple Inc. litigation#Amazon \"App Store\"}}\n\n[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] filed a lawsuit against Amazon for using a similar name to the Apple [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/TECH/web/03/22/apple.amazon.app.fast/index.html | title=Apple sues Amazon over 'app store' name | publisher=CNN Tech | date=March 22, 2011 | accessdate=September 15, 2012 | author=Eaton, Kit}}</ref> Amazon claimed that the term was too generic to be trademarked, and asked the judge to dismiss the suit.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://arstechnica.com/apple/2011/04/amazon-responds-to-apple-app-store-is-generic-toss-the-suit/ | title=Amazon responds to Apple: \"app store\" is generic, toss the suit | publisher=Ars Technica | date=April 26, 2011 | accessdate=September 15, 2012 | author=Cheng, Jacqui}}</ref> Apple responded to Amazon's attempted dismissal of the lawsuit by claiming that Amazon was tarnishing the trademark by using the name.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.electronista.com/articles/11/06/10/apple.filing.says.amazon.drags.down.app.store.name/ | title=Apple claims Amazon Appstore 'tarnishes' App Store trademark | publisher=Electronista | date=June 10, 2011 | accessdate=September 15, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101134122/http://www.electronista.com/articles/11/06/10/apple.filing.says.amazon.drags.down.app.store.name/ | archive-date=November 1, 2012 | url-status=dead }}</ref> A federal judge denied Apple's request for a preliminary injunction, disagreeing with Amazon's claim that the term is generic, and citing that Apple had not established \"a likelihood of confusion\" with Amazon's services to obtain an injunction.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/07/us-apple-amazon-ruling-idUSTRE76604S20110707 | title=Judge rejects Apple bid for injunction against Amazon | publisher=Reuters | date=July 6, 2011 | accessdate=September 15, 2012 | author=Levine, Dan}}</ref> Apple changed its complaint after Amazon started advertising the [[Kindle Fire]], now saying that Amazon is trying to confuse customers further by dropping the \"for Android\" part of \"Amazon Appstore for Android.\" In the amended complaint, Apple wrote that \"Amazon's use is also likely to lessen the goodwill associated with Apple's App Store service and Apple products designed to utilize Apple's App Store service by associating Apple's App Store service with the inferior qualities of Amazon's service.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.wired.com/business/2011/11/kindle-fire-app-store-suit/ | title=Kindle Fire Dragged Into Apple's 'App Store' Suit Against Amazon | publisher=Wired | work=Ars Technica | date=November 18, 2011 | accessdate=September 15, 2012 | author=Cheng, Jacqui}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Apple's claims were rejected by a US District judge, who argued that the company presented no evidence that Amazon had \"[attempted] to mimic Apple's site or advertising\", or communicated that its service \"possesses the characteristics and qualities that the public has come to expect from the Apple APP STORE and/or Apple products.\"<ref name=ars-rejected>{{cite web|title=No app for that: Apple's false ad suit over Amazon Appstore thrown out|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/01/no-app-for-that-apples-false-ad-suit-over-amazon-appstore-thrown-out/|work=Ars Technica|accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> In July 2013, Apple dropped the case.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bostic |first=Kevin |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/13/07/09/apple-drops-app-store-lawsuit-against-amazon-says-no-need-to-pursue-case |title=Apple drops 'App Store' lawsuit against Amazon, says no need to pursue case |publisher=Appleinsider.com |date=2013-07-09 |accessdate=2014-01-02}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of mobile software distribution platforms]]\n*[[Google Play]]\n*[[App Store (iOS)]]\n*[[BlackBerry World]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://www.amazon.com/mobile-apps/b/ref%3Dtopnav_storetab_mas?ie%3DUTF8&node%3D2350149011}}\n* {{official website|https://developer.amazon.com/public}}\n* {{Dmoz|Computers/Software/Operating_Systems/Android/Markets|Android markets}}\n\n{{Amazon}}\n{{Software digital distribution platforms|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Amazon (company)]]\n[[Category:Mobile software distribution platforms]]\n[[Category:Online marketplaces of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Amazon Appstore for Android\n| logo                   = Amazon.com-Logo.svg\n| logo size              = 200px\n| screenshot             = Amazon App Store.png\n| screenshot size        = 200px\n| caption                = Amazon Appstore for Android\n| developer              = [[Amazon.com]]\n| released               =  March 22, 2011\n| status                 = Active / 800,000+ apps\n| latest_release_version = release-32.52.1.0.204529.0_800923810\n| latest_release_date    = {{Start date and age|2020|3|10|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/getappstore \n|title=Install Amazon Appstore|publisher=Amazon|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n| operating_system       = [[Android Operating System|Android]]<br/>[[Fire OS]]\n| genre                  = [[Software update]], [[digital distribution]]\n| license                = [[proprietary software|Proprietary]]\n| website                = {{URL|https://www.amazon.com/getappstore}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Amazon Appstore for Android''' is an [[app store]] for the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] operating system operated by [[Amazon.com]]. It was opened on March 22, 2011 and was made available in nearly 200 countries.<ref>{{cite web|author=Amazon.com |url=https://developer.amazon.com/post/Tx3IJP9TKDQOXS5/Developers-Can-Now-Distribute-Apps-in-Nearly-200-Countries-Worldwide-on-Amazon.html |title=Developers Can Now Distribute Apps in Nearly 200 Countries Worldwide on Amazon - Amazon Mobile App Distribution Blog |publisher=Developer.amazon.com |date=2013-05-23 |accessdate=2013-11-27}}</ref> Developers are paid 70% of the [[list price]] of the app or in-app purchase.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sigitarinto.com/2011/03/22/amazon-app-store/ |title=Amazon Appstore &#124; Android |publisher=SigitArinto.com |date=2011-03-22 |accessdate=2011-04-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827070545/http://sigitarinto.com/2011/03/22/amazon-app-store/ |archivedate=2011-08-27 }}</ref>\n\nOn September 28, 2011, Amazon launched the [[Kindle Fire]] tablet.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ned Potter via Good Morning America |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/amazon-kindle-fire-announced-jeff-bezos-beat-apple/story?id=14623497 |title=Amazon Tablet: Kindle Fire Announced by Jeff Bezos to Beat Apple iPad for $199, Relative Bargain - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2011-09-28 |accessdate=2013-11-27}}</ref> The tablet, designed for [[media consumption]] in the Amazon ecosystem, relies solely on the Amazon Appstore for its marketplace, eschewing [[Google Play]]. Alongside the tablet was a new design for the Amazon Appstore, intended to better integrate with the tablet's user interface.\n\nOn June 18, 2014, [[BlackBerry Limited|BlackBerry]] announced an official relationship with Amazon, which includes access to the Amazon Appstore in [[BlackBerry 10]].3.<ref name=verge-amazonapp>{{cite web|title=BlackBerry will bring thousands of apps from Amazon's store to its phones|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/6/18/5820472/blackberry-phones-getting-amazon-appstore-apps-in-bb10-3|website=The Verge|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\n\nThe Amazon Appstore included the \"Free App of the Day\" feature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andromint.com/google-play-store-vs-amazon-appstore/ |title=Amazon Appstore Compared with Google Play |work=Andromint.com |date=28 October 2013 |accessdate=2013-10-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031052750/http://www.andromint.com/google-play-store-vs-amazon-appstore/ |archivedate=31 October 2013 }}</ref>  Every day, an application, frequently a game, was offered for free. On the launch day, this game was [[Angry Birds Rio]] (Ad-Free), in itself a promotional game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2011-03-22/advertise/bal-new-amazon-android-app-store-1-free-app--day-20110322_1_app-store-free-app-amazon |title=New Amazon Android App Store - 1 Free App / Day - Baltimore Sun |publisher=Articles.baltimoresun.com |date=2011-03-22 |accessdate=2011-04-05 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110412175431/http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2011-03-22/advertise/bal-new-amazon-android-app-store-1-free-app--day-20110322_1_app-store-free-app-amazon |archivedate=12 April 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On The European launch day, the free app was [[Angry Birds (video game)|Angry Birds]] (Ad-Free). The Free App of the Day feature made an exception to Amazon's payments, instead giving the developer none of the list price during the featured day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gigaom.com/2011/07/05/amazon-appstore-not-so-amazing/ |title=Amazon Appstore, Not so Amazing |publisher=GigaOM|date=2011-07-05|accessdate=2011-07-06| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110709060730/http://gigaom.com/2011/07/05/amazon-appstore-not-so-amazing/| archivedate= 9 July 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe store's \"Test Drive\" feature allowed users to try an application in their web browser by launching a virtual copy of Android in the [[Amazon EC2]] [[cloud computing|cloud]] for half an hour.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jason Kincaid |url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/03/22/amazon-android-app-store-3/ |title=Amazon's Android App Store Launches: Test Drive Apps Directly From Your Browser |publisher=Techcrunch.com |date=2011-03-22 |accessdate=2011-04-05| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110328065244/http://techcrunch.com/2011/03/22/amazon-android-app-store-3/| archivedate= 28 March 2011| url-status= live}}</ref> The Test Drive service was decommissioned in 2015, Amazon saying that the service had been in decline, partly due to many apps not supporting the feature, and the increasing prevalence of the \"free-to-play\" business model making it obsolete.<ref>Perez, Sarah. \"Amazon Shuts Down TestDrive.\" TechCrunch. TechCrunch, 17 Apr. 2015. Web. 20 July 2015. [https://techcrunch.com/2015/04/17/amazon-shuts-down-testdrive-the-appstore-feature-that-let-you-try-apps-before-downloading/ Amazon Shuts Down TestDrive]</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Amazon introduced [[Amazon Coin]]s as a form of payment for purchasing apps, games, and [[in-app purchases]] from the store.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/may/14/amazon-coins-virtual-currency|title=Amazon launches Coins virtual currency|last=Flood|first=Alison|date=2013-05-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Android applications==\nAs of October 9, 2019, the Amazon Appstore features 487,083 applications available for download.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/307330/number-of-available-apps-in-the-amazon-appstore/|title=Amazon Appstore: number of available apps by quarter 2018 {{!}} Statistic|website=Statista|language=en|access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref>\n\nOnly a few of the most popular apps available on the Google Play Store and the [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] are also available on the Amazon Appstore. For example, [[Facebook, Inc.|the Facebook company]] offers [[Facebook]], Facebook Lite, [[Instagram]], [[Facebook Messenger|Messenger]] and [[Messenger Kids]] in all stores. However, the company does not offer [[IGTV]] separately from Instagram on the Amazon Appstore, nor does it offer [[WhatsApp]], Messenger Lite, Boomerang or Layout.\n\n===History of app growth===\nWhen the Amazon Appstore for Android launched in March 2011, it had about 3,800 apps. It reached 80,000 apps in June 2013 and 240,000 apps in June 2014.<ref>[http://www.androidcentral.com/amazon-appstore-triples-selection-240000-apps Amazon Appstore triples selection to 240,000 apps] June 2014.</ref> In June 2015, the app store had nearly 334,000 apps.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/mobile-apps/b?node=2350149011 Amazon App Store for Android]. Retrieved 23 June 2015.</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nShortly after the Amazon Appstore launch, the [[International Game Developers Association]] (IGDA) published an open letter expressing concerns that were primarily aimed at Amazon's distribution terms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://igdaboard.wordpress.com/2011/04/14/important-advisory-about-amazon%E2%80%99s-appstore-distribution-terms-2/ |title=Important Advisory about Amazon's Appstore Distribution Terms |publisher=[[International Game Developers Association]] |accessdate=2011-05-14|quote=''We are not aware of any other retailer having a formal policy of paying a supplier just 20% of the supplier's minimum list price without the supplier's permission.(...)If you ever conduct even a temporary price promotion in another market, you must permanently lower your list price in Amazon's market''| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110430031238/http://igdaboard.wordpress.com/2011/04/14/important-advisory-about-amazon%E2%80%99s-appstore-distribution-terms-2/| archivedate= 30 April 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/appsblog/2011/apr/14/amazon-android-appstore-igda |title=IGDA warns Android game developers about Amazon's Appstore terms|publisher=[[guardian.co.uk]] |date=2011-04-14 |accessdate=2011-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/34108/IGDA_Outlines_Significant_Concerns_Over_Amazon_Appstore_Terms.php |title=IGDA Outlines 'Significant Concerns' Over Amazon Appstore Terms|publisher=[[Gamasutra]] |date=2011-04-14 |accessdate=2011-05-14| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110510075823/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/34108/IGDA_Outlines_Significant_Concerns_Over_Amazon_Appstore_Terms.php| archivedate= 10 May 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> The main concerns about the conditions were that Appstore terms force developers to permanently lower their AppStore prices if ever they do promotions on other stores, and that Amazon could choose to lower the price of an application while deciding to reduce the developer's share without having to ask permission. Following this address, Amazon clarified the Appstore developer agreement,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amazonappstoredev.com/2011/04/clarification-about-amazon-appstore-developer-agreement.html |title=Clarification about Amazon Appstore Developer Agreement|publisher=[[Amazon.com, Inc.]] |date=2011-04-15 |accessdate=2011-05-14| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110511085347/http://www.amazonappstoredev.com/2011/04/clarification-about-amazon-appstore-developer-agreement.html| archivedate= 11 May 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> but this did not assuage the IGDA's concerns, which declared that \"Amazon's terms represent a threat to game developers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://igdaboard.wordpress.com/2011/04/19/amazon%E2%80%99s-clarification-fails-to-address-game-developer-concerns/ |title=Amazon's clarification fails to address game developer concerns |publisher=[[International Game Developers Association]] |date=2011-04-19 |accessdate=2011-05-14 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511093033/http://igdaboard.wordpress.com/2011/04/19/amazon%E2%80%99s-clarification-fails-to-address-game-developer-concerns/ |archivedate=11 May 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canardpc.com/news-52508-tir_de_barrage_contre_amazon.html |title=Tir de barrage contre Amazon |publisher=[[Canard PC]] |date=2011-04-14 |accessdate=2011-05-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518041449/http://www.canardpc.com/news-52508-tir_de_barrage_contre_amazon.html |archive-date=2011-05-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, the Swedish developer Bithack pulled its ''Apparatus'' application from the Appstore and published an open letter explaining that the store was a \"disaster\" for indie developers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bithack.se/news/apparatus-amazon-july-4-2011.html|title=Apparatus will be pulled from Amazon Appstore|quote=''If you are a small indie development team, or possibly even alone, don't bother with Amazon Appstore. Create a great app, publish it on Android Market, and provide great customer support. You will never succeed on Amazon Appstore without a big wallet, or at least an established reputation so that Amazon puts value behind their promises.''|publisher=bithack.se|date=2011-07-04|accessdate=2011-07-15|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110705190345/http://bithack.se/news/apparatus-amazon-july-4-2011.html|archivedate=2011-07-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> The main problems related to the very slow review process, the absence of any means to filter unsupported devices, and that Amazon changed the price of the application without consulting the developer,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/2084090/game-developer-pulls-app-amazon-appstore |title=Game developer pulls app from Amazon Appstore over problems |quote=''The final problem was that Amazon changed the price without consulting the developer. The price was cut to $0.99, only a quarter of its original price, which, while perhaps good for players, is not good for the developer.''|publisher=[[The Inquirer]] |date=2011-07-05|accessdate=2011-07-15}}</ref> leading to the IGDA reiterating its warnings concerning Amazon's policy once again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2011/07/08/igda-still-unhappy-with-amazon-appstore-policies/|title=IGDA still unhappy with Amazon Appstore policies|publisher=Joystiq|date=2011-07-08|accessdate=2011-07-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714112306/http://www.joystiq.com/2011/07/08/igda-still-unhappy-with-amazon-appstore-policies/|archive-date=2011-07-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Accusation of trademark infringement by Apple ==\n{{See also|Apple Inc. litigation#Amazon \"App Store\"}}\n\n[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] filed a lawsuit against Amazon for using a similar name to the Apple [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/TECH/web/03/22/apple.amazon.app.fast/index.html | title=Apple sues Amazon over 'app store' name | publisher=CNN Tech | date=March 22, 2011 | accessdate=September 15, 2012 | author=Eaton, Kit}}</ref> Amazon claimed that the term was too generic to be trademarked, and asked the judge to dismiss the suit.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://arstechnica.com/apple/2011/04/amazon-responds-to-apple-app-store-is-generic-toss-the-suit/ | title=Amazon responds to Apple: \"app store\" is generic, toss the suit | publisher=Ars Technica | date=April 26, 2011 | accessdate=September 15, 2012 | author=Cheng, Jacqui}}</ref> Apple responded to Amazon's attempted dismissal of the lawsuit by claiming that Amazon was tarnishing the trademark by using the name.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.electronista.com/articles/11/06/10/apple.filing.says.amazon.drags.down.app.store.name/ | title=Apple claims Amazon Appstore 'tarnishes' App Store trademark | publisher=Electronista | date=June 10, 2011 | accessdate=September 15, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101134122/http://www.electronista.com/articles/11/06/10/apple.filing.says.amazon.drags.down.app.store.name/ | archive-date=November 1, 2012 | url-status=dead }}</ref> A federal judge denied Apple's request for a preliminary injunction, disagreeing with Amazon's claim that the term is generic, and citing that Apple had not established \"a likelihood of confusion\" with Amazon's services to obtain an injunction.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/07/us-apple-amazon-ruling-idUSTRE76604S20110707 | title=Judge rejects Apple bid for injunction against Amazon | publisher=Reuters | date=July 6, 2011 | accessdate=September 15, 2012 | author=Levine, Dan}}</ref> Apple changed its complaint after Amazon started advertising the [[Kindle Fire]], now saying that Amazon is trying to confuse customers further by dropping the \"for Android\" part of \"Amazon Appstore for Android.\" In the amended complaint, Apple wrote that \"Amazon's use is also likely to lessen the goodwill associated with Apple's App Store service and Apple products designed to utilize Apple's App Store service by associating Apple's App Store service with the inferior qualities of Amazon's service.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.wired.com/business/2011/11/kindle-fire-app-store-suit/ | title=Kindle Fire Dragged Into Apple's 'App Store' Suit Against Amazon | publisher=Wired | work=Ars Technica | date=November 18, 2011 | accessdate=September 15, 2012 | author=Cheng, Jacqui}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Apple's claims were rejected by a US District judge, who argued that the company presented no evidence that Amazon had \"[attempted] to mimic Apple's site or advertising\", or communicated that its service \"possesses the characteristics and qualities that the public has come to expect from the Apple APP STORE and/or Apple products.\"<ref name=ars-rejected>{{cite web|title=No app for that: Apple's false ad suit over Amazon Appstore thrown out|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/01/no-app-for-that-apples-false-ad-suit-over-amazon-appstore-thrown-out/|work=Ars Technica|accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> In July 2013, Apple dropped the case.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bostic |first=Kevin |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/13/07/09/apple-drops-app-store-lawsuit-against-amazon-says-no-need-to-pursue-case |title=Apple drops 'App Store' lawsuit against Amazon, says no need to pursue case |publisher=Appleinsider.com |date=2013-07-09 |accessdate=2014-01-02}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of mobile software distribution platforms]]\n*[[Google Play]]\n*[[App Store (iOS)]]\n*[[BlackBerry World]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://www.amazon.com/mobile-apps/b/ref%3Dtopnav_storetab_mas?ie%3DUTF8&node%3D2350149011}}\n* {{official website|https://developer.amazon.com/public}}\n* {{Dmoz|Computers/Software/Operating_Systems/Android/Markets|Android markets}}\n\n{{Amazon}}\n{{Software digital distribution platforms|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Amazon (company)]]\n[[Category:Mobile software distribution platforms]]\n[[Category:Online marketplaces of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "KressInsel", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amazon_Appstore"}
